@Node "Introduction" "EqEd.guide/Introduction"
@Next "Requirements"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"

Introduction
============

   Until now the wordprocessors available for the Amiga computers have
been missing several of the features, which wordprocessors for the PC
have. One of these is the ability to write complex mathematical
expressions, which is important if you are making a scientific paper,
report and such. So far the only choice has been to use LaTeX, which
makes great output, but it takes time to learn, since it's actually a
whole programming language.  It is also easier (but not necessarily
faster) to use a WYSIWYG interface, especially if you are just doing a
few expressions.

   This is what my program does. It lets you design your expressions in
a (hopefully) easy to understand WYSIWYG manner, and export it for
insertion in your favourite wordprocessor like FinalWriter, WordWorth
or a DTP-program like PageSetter.

   This is released as a public beta version. This means it doesn't have
all the functions the final release will have and probably it contains
numerous bugs. This manual is by no means finished, but look at @{"Future" Link "Future"}
and @{"Register" Link "Register"} for more information on this and the betarelease.

   For a quick try read the @{"Installation" Link "Installation"} part first please, and then
start it. Unknown functions is described by pressing help-key.

   Here is a list of some of EqEd's features:

   * It's WYSIWYG. No need to remember how a fraction or integral is
     done

   * It support @{"Multiple lines" Link "Multiple lines"} and @{"Multiple columns" Link "Multiple columns"} - IMPROVED in v0.96

   * Simple tables are supported - NEW in v0.96.

   * Matrix function

   * Unlimited nesting of fractions, roots etc.

   * Output in @{"LaTeX" Link "LaTeX"}, @{"PostScript" Link "PostScript"} and @{"IFF" Link "IFF"}

   * Unlimited size of equations

   * Userdefineable shortcut keys - see @{"Set Key" Link "Set Key"}

   * Userdefineable toolbar with drag & drop

   * ARexx interface

   * Uses @{"MUI" Link "MUI"} 3.x - some might thinks that's a fault, not a feature :-)

   * Online help. Press Help-key with pointer upon a gadget

   * Bubble help for a short message.

   * Clipboard support

   * Uses scalable fonts - IMPROVED in v0.96


@EndNode

@Node "Requirements" "EqEd.guide/Requirements"
@Next "Copyright"
@Prev "Introduction"
@Toc "Main"

Requirements
============

   Eqed needs:

   - OS 2.04 or better

   - @{"MUI" Link "MUI"} version 3.2 or better

   - at least 1.5 megabyte of FREE memory

   - about 2 megabytes of harddisk-space

   - type1.library

   - Installer from Commodore

   The program can be used with disks, in theory. The amount of
diskspace needed depends however on the resolutions wanted. If for
instance you want to make equations for a 300x300 dpi printer and save
in IFF-format, the fonts alone needs over 800kb of space in memory and
800kb cached and uncompressed (no XPK) on disk. That's why 1.5 megs of
ram and 2 megs of diskspace is an absolut minimum.

   Saving IFF-files in a decent resolution demands at least 0.5 MB more.
If XPK is installed the disk usage can be reduced considerably.  Of
course a fast processor won't be bad either as @{"MUI" Link "MUI"} isn't that fast and
the current version of EqEd is a bit slow.  A stock A1200 with harddisk
should be able to run it with out any problems, but of course no
wordprocessor can run at the same time.


@EndNode

