Installation
============

   Installation should be easier from version EqEd v0.96 than before,
but I still suggest you browse through the following.

   I guess you have already unpacked the archive, since you can read
this and this should have made a directory with EqEd and a few extra
files.

   To install simply double click on the "Install EqEd" icon, and follow
the instructions. Some of the things in the installation might not be,
completly clear, so I've supplied a step by step description of the
installation here:

   1. After the presentation, you tell the script where to make the EqEd
drawer, which will contain the program and the documentation.

   2. You can then install the boring Commodore-look icons, if you don't
like MagicWB.

   3. The examples are a few files, which can be displayed in EqEd,
just to demonstrate what EqEd is capable of.

   4. EqEd uses scalable fonts, which take quite a long time to
generate, so to avoid this EqEd features a fontcache-mechanism.
Unfortunately it takes a long time to generate such a cachefile, so in
order to be able test EqEd right away, a default cache is supplied. I
suggest you install this. To find out more about fontcache read the
@{"Cache" Link "Cache"} section.

   5. The supplied ARexx scripts are for FinalWriter 1 to 4, and goes
quite a long way to integrate EqEd into FinalWriter. You will need to
setup FinalWriter too, so read the @{"ARexx" Link "ARexx"} section.

   6. EqEd uses standard outline font libraries, which means you can
use standard Compugraphic fonts supplied with WB2.1 and above.  Since
you probably don't have a full symbol font in that format, you will
have to use the "Type1.library" by Amish S. Dave available on Aminet,
which uses Postscript fonts as outline fonts. The four supplied fonts
are such Postscript fonts. You will probably have to install the Symbol
font, but the rest is optional, if you have other Postscript fonts.
Note that the fonts isn't needed until you want to generate a new
fontcache or use the Postscript output.

   If you have FinalWriter you should place the fonts in a directory,
which has the assign "PSFONTS:" - see @{"FinalWriter" Link "FinalWriter"}, otherwise you can
place them anywhere.

   To use the postscript fonts, you will first have to run the
T1Manager, which comes with Type1.library and install the Symbol font
and maybe also the Utopia fonts, before you can use them in EqEd. The
documentation for the Type1.library contains information on how to
install the fonts. You should read it, but in comes down to this: make
a directory in your fonts: directory (eg: "eqed_fonts") and add this to
the fonts: assign by issuing "assign fonts: fonts:eqed_fonts add" from
the shell. Then run the T1Manager and select the "eqed_fonts"-assign
from the "Font Drawer:" cycle gadget.  Then select 'install' and choose
the postscript-fonts you want to use. Again: read the
type1-documentation too!

   7. The AFM files contains information about the fonts, which EqEd
needs when it is saving Postscript output. So these should only be
installed, if you need postscript output, and EqEd is probably the only
program that needs the AFM files, so just install them in the EqEd
directory.

   8. If you install the FinalWriter ARexx scripts, you will need to
assign "EqEd:", so that the script can find EqEd. This can be done
automaticly.

   Now you should be ready to have a test run with EqEd. If you like
what you see and want to use EqEd, you will have to change the
preferences, so that paths for the fonts are correct. You might also
want to generate other fontcaches. Refer to the @{"Preference window" Link "Preference window"} pages
for more information.


@EndNode

@Node "Basic usage" "EqEd.guide/Basic usage"
@Next "Main window"
@Prev "Installation"
@Toc "Main"

Basic usage
===========

   Using EqEd should be quite straight forward. Enter the expression
using the keyboard as usual for text and number, changing the font with
the two cyclegadgets.  Special mathematical symbol can be entered using
the toolbars. Editing can be done by both keyboard and mouse, cutting
and copying parts of the expression to be placed elsewhere in the
expression. The return key enables multiple lines in the expression.
For faster insertion of symbols, function, greek letters you can use
the @{"Set Key" Link "Set Key"} menu to create keyboard shortcuts for those or drag a
symbol from a tool to one of the eight userbuttons. Use @{"Save prefs" Link "Save prefs"} to
remember the shortcuts after quiting the program.  Columns can be made
by displaying the @{"Horizontal ruler" Link "Horizontal ruler"} and placing tab stops with the mouse.

   The expression can be saved in six different formats, see
@{"Output Format" Link "Output Format"} about those.

   This should cover the basic usage. More detailed information is
available in the following sections @{"Main window" Link "Main window"}, @{"Keys" Link "Keys"}, @{"Tables" Link "Tables"} and @{"Menus" Link "Menus"}


@EndNode

@Node "Main window" "EqEd.guide/Main window"
@Next "Preference window"
@Prev "Basic usage"
@Toc "Main"

Main window
===========

   The main window consists of areas laid out as this:

@{"Symbols" Link "Symbols"}                        @{"Mode" Link "Mode"}

@{"Symbols" Link "Symbols"}   @{"Lines" Link "Lines"}    @{"Functions" Link "Functions"} @{"Font" Link "Font"}

@{"User buttons" Link "User buttons"} (These can be turned off!)

@{"Tab type" Link "Tab type"} @{"Horizontal ruler" Link "Horizontal ruler"} (These can be turned off!)

             @{"Editing Area" Link "Editing Area"}

@{"Vertical ruler" Link "Vertical ruler"} (This can be turned off!)

   Click on the appropriate gadget for a description.


@EndNode

@Node "Functions" "EqEd.guide/Functions"
@Next "Symbols"
@Prev "Main window"
@Toc "Main window"

Functions
=========

   In expressions the names of variables are often written in an
italics-font, while functions are written in non-italics. To avoid
changing @{"Mode" Link "Mode"} and typing too much, the most common functions is listed
in a seperate window.  Just click on the gadget called "Sin...", and
you will get a listview of the functions. Doubleclicking will enter the
function at the cursor.

   The window has a menu called "Fastclose". When this one is set the
window will close itself when a function has been selected. This helps
to reduce the amount of open windows.

   Some of the functions has limits placed above or/and below the
function name.  If you don't need the limit, just move the cursor out
of field and the limit disappears.  Move the cursor back into the limit
and it will reappear.  Currently there is no way to get limits to a
function which doesn't have it buildin already - this might change if
there is a need.

   If you need a specific function often, you can make a shortcut key
with the @{"Set Key" Link "Set Key"} menu.


@EndNode

@Node "Symbols" "EqEd.guide/Symbols"
@Next "Lines"
@Prev "Functions"
@Toc "Main window"

Symbols
=======

   The lot of buttons with symbols on give access to a lot of
mathematical symbols, greek letters (see also @{"Font" Link "Font"}) and things like
fractions and roots. The symbols pretty much give what they look like!
Notice that brackets will scale according to the text inside them and
that a few symbols exists in two sizes! If an area is selected most
symbols will replace that area, but a few will instead insert the
marked inside the "symbol" e.g. between brackets or under the rootsign.
The new matrix function is located in the same window as the fraction
and root symbols.

   Shortcut keys is done in the @{"Set Key" Link "Set Key"} menu.

   The symbol windows has two menus. The "Change Layout" will change
layout of the buttons from horizontal to vertical and back again. If
"Fast Close" is set the window will close when a symbol has been
selected.  Note that the main window has menus to change these settings
for all windows - see @{"Symbol Windows" Link "Symbol Windows"}

   Saving preferences with @{"Save prefs" Link "Save prefs"} will save the status of "Fast
Close" and the layout of the buttons!


@EndNode

@Node "Lines" "EqEd.guide/Lines"
@Next "Mode"
@Prev "Symbols"
@Toc "Main window"

Lines
=====

   This is window that is used, when creating tables. Use the listview
to choose the type of line that should be placed around the cell, where
the cursor is. The five leftmost buttons, will change the lines around
the cell according to the image on the button. Note that clicking one
more time will remove the line again, so you don't have to choose the
"None" line type. The last button, doesn't do anything right now, since
EqEd currently doesn't support line operations on multiple cells.

   See @{"Tables" Link "Tables"} for more information and examples.


@EndNode

@Node "Mode" "EqEd.guide/Mode"
@Next "Font"
@Prev "Lines"
@Toc "Main window"

Mode
====

   If you look at mathematical expressions in books, most use an
italics-font for the variables and constants in the expression, but
roman for functions. This is also the default in EqEd, but sometimes
you might need to write a word or sentence, and then you can use the
Mode gadget. It lets you select between three modes:

   MathMode: italics-font and default mode.

   TextMode: no italic letters - use for written words.

   BoldMode: Uses bold letters - use for vectors for instance.

   If no block is selected, choosing a mode doesn't appear to have an
effect, but when you start to write the letters will correspond to the
chosen mode.  When you move about in the expression, the mode gadget
changes to reflect the mode of the symbol to left of the cursor, and
writing will be in the same mode, unless another is selected.

   If a block is selected, the whole block will become the mode you
choose in the mode block.

   The mode command is also available in the @{"Textmode" Link "Textmode"}, @{"Mathmode" Link "Mathmode"} and
@{"Boldmode" Link "Boldmode"} menus. This gives keyboard shortcuts.


@EndNode

@Node "Font" "EqEd.guide/Font"
@Next "User buttons"
@Prev "Mode"
@Toc "Main window"

Font
====

   This works as the @{"Mode" Link "Mode"} gadget except this switches between roman
letters and greek letters. When greek is selected, greek letters can be
entered by pressing the key, which represent the roman letter that
corresponds to the greek letter.  It is also possible to use an extra
font, which you or somebody else may have made, which contains
mathematical symbols not in the standard font. If no extra font is
used, it defaults to the Roman font. Note that @{"LaTeX" Link "LaTeX"}-output doesn't
support the extra font!

   It doesn't operate on blocks, though, as that has little value.

   If a single greek letter is used often between roman letters, you
can use the @{"Set Key" Link "Set Key"} to redefine a key to give that letter. Entering
that won't change the font, so you can enter the greek letter without
having change the mode at all (normally you would have to change font
twice!)

   You can also use the greek symbols available in the toolbars if you
don't remember/know the corresponding key.

   The font command is also available in the @{"Roman" Link "Roman"} and @{"Greek" Link "Greek"} menus.


@EndNode

@Node "User buttons" "EqEd.guide/User buttons"
@Next "Tab type"
@Prev "Font"
@Toc "Main window"

User buttons
============

   If you some symbols a lot, but don't want to have the windows open
all the time and can't remember the shortcut key, you can define one of
these eight userdefinable buttons to that symbol. To set a button
simply drag the symbol from the tool windows and drop on one of the
eight user buttons.

   The buttons can be switched on and off by the @{"Show symbolbar" Link "Show symbolbar"} menu.


@EndNode

@Node "Tab type" "EqEd.guide/Tab type"
@Next "Horizontal ruler"
@Prev "User buttons"
@Toc "Main window"

Tab type
========

   This area is only shown if both the @{"Horizontal ruler" Link "Horizontal ruler"} and the
@{"Vertical ruler" Link "Vertical ruler"} is shown. Clicking on the the area will make it cycle
through the five kinds of tab stops available. These can now be placed
on the horizontal ruler by clicking on it.

   See @{"Horizontal ruler" Link "Horizontal ruler"} for more information


@EndNode

@Node "Horizontal ruler" "EqEd.guide/Horizontal ruler"
@Next "Vertical ruler"
@Prev "Tab type"
@Toc "Main window"

Horizontal ruler
================

   This can be toggled on and off by the @{"Show top ruler" Link "Show top ruler"} menu.

   When displayed it shows a ruler in either centimeters or inches, so
one can see how wide the equation is. It most important task is to allow
the setting of tab stops. Simply select the wanted @{"Tab type" Link "Tab type"} and click
on the ruler where you want it placed. These tabstop is now used when
Tab is pressed. Note that when inside a matrix you are setting tabstops
for that matrix - this is how multiple columns in matrices are done!
The tabstop marked with a simple vertical line, is used to mark where
the cells of a table ends - see @{"Tables" Link "Tables"} for more information.

   You can move the old tabstop by pointing at it with the mouse and
then drag it to its new location. Dragging it outside the ruler, will
remove it.

   If you hold down one of the <Shift> button while you drag a tabstop,
all the tabstops to the right of the moved one, will move too.

   Holding down <Ctrl> while adding or moving a tabstop, will only
change the tabstop in the current line and downwards, thus allowing to
make complex tables.

   Tab stops has a few support menus: @{"Copy Ruler" Link "Copy Ruler"}, @{"Paste Ruler" Link "Paste Ruler"},
@{"Clear Ruler" Link "Clear Ruler"} and @{"Edit Tabs" Link "Edit Tabs"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Vertical ruler" "EqEd.guide/Vertical ruler"
@Next "Editing Area"
@Prev "Horizontal ruler"
@Toc "Main window"

Vertical ruler
==============

   This can be toggled on and off by the @{"Show left ruler" Link "Show left ruler"} menu.

   This displays the distances like the @{"Horizontal ruler" Link "Horizontal ruler"} does, but
instead of tabstops it has some thick lines in the ruler, which shows
where each line in the equation begins. Selecting and dragging these
with the mouse, will change the spacing between the lines.  When inside
a matrix it will display lines for the matrix lines!


@EndNode

@Node "Editing Area" "EqEd.guide/Editing Area"
@Prev "Vertical ruler"
@Toc "Main window"

Editing Area
============

   This is where it all happens. Here the entered expression is
displayed, as you enter it. Expressions is entered using the @{"Keys" Link "Keys"} and
the previously described gadgets. It is also possible to use the mouse
for placing the cursor or marking blocks. Clicking somewhere moves the
cursor to the symbol you clicked on, while pressing the left button
somewhere and then dragging the mouse across some of the expression
will mark this, just as if you used the @{"Mark" Link "Mark"} menu.

   If you want to delete a larger area just mark it and press delete or
a symbol to replace the deleted.


@EndNode

@Node "Preference window" "EqEd.guide/Preference window"
@Next "Keys"
@Prev "Main window"
@Toc "Main"

Preference window
=================

   The preference window is for entering information on which fonts EqEd
shall use and similar data.   It is shown when the user selects
@{"Set Prefs" Link "Set Prefs"}.  It will also be shown, if EqEd is missing information about
the fonts when it wants to save something.

   The window has the following six pages:

@{"Misc" Link "Misc"}

@{"Fonts" Link "Fonts"}

@{"Output" Link "Output"}

@{"AFM" Link "AFM"}

@{"Rexx" Link "Rexx"}

@{"Cache" Link "Cache"}

   The "Save", "Use" and "Cancel" buttons should be obvious.


@EndNode

@Node "Misc" "EqEd.guide/Misc"
@Toc "Preference window"

Miscellaneous
=============

   Here there are various settings:

   * The decimal group defines, whether to use a comma or period as the
     centering character, when using decimalcentered tabstops.

   * The unit changes the units on the two rulers and in the @{"Edit Tabs" Link "Edit Tabs"}
     window.

   * The colors sets, which colors are to be used in drawing the
     equation on screen.

   * EqEd v0.96 implements a new memoryhandler and the last gadget
     defines how much memory EqEd should try to leave free. Note that
     this works best under OS3.0, where the system can ask EqEd to free
     some memory.  Under OS2.x you better not set this too low.


@EndNode

@Node "Fonts" "EqEd.guide/Fonts"
@Toc "Preference window"

Fonts
=====

   Here you set the path to the outline fonts, which EqEd uses to
generate fontcaches, or simply uses when it doesn't have a fontcache.
Note that it is the files ending with ".otag" that you have to select,
not the Postscript or ".font" files! You can leave the Extra field
empty, EqEd will then simply use the Roman font.

   The font size is in points, meaning 1/72 inch, which is the standard
unit in wordprocessors.


@EndNode

@Node "Output" "EqEd.guide/Output"
@Toc "Preference window"

Output
======

   This is made up of three equal groups. In each group you either
select a fontcache, which has already been made - see @{"Cache" Link "Cache"} - in which
case the resolution is set automaticly, or you remove the cache name,
and set the resolution manually. If you don't use a cache EqEd will use
the information in @{"Fonts" Link "Fonts"} to render the needed characters on the fly.
This is only recommended on fast machines.

   The "screen" group refers to what EqEd uses on the screen of course,
and "IFF" is for saving IFF files. I recommend that you a resolution of
at least 150x150 on the screen, whereby you effectivly zoom in by a
factor of two or more.

   The "preview" group information is used, when saving Postscript files
with preview images - see @{"PostScript+Preview" Link "PostScript+Preview"}. Normally you can just use
the same fontcache as the screen, since the Wordprocessor will scale
the preview image.


@EndNode

@Node "AFM" "EqEd.guide/AFM"
@Toc "Preference window"

AFM
===

   Here you setup the paths to the AFM-files, which EqEd uses when
saving @{"PostScript" Link "PostScript"}. Note that the "Extra" field doesn't have to be used.

   If you have a postscript printer you should include the postscript
font in the EPS-file. This is done by selecting the download font
button, and entering the path where the PostScript fonts are placed.
These should have exactly the same name as the AFM files except there
shouldn't be any extensions.

   Please note that including fonts makes the EPS-output a lot bigger.


@EndNode

@Node "Rexx" "EqEd.guide/Rexx"
@Toc "Preference window"

Rexx
====

   EqEd can place ARexx scripts on the function keys F1-F5, and this is
where you select which scripts to use. See @{"ARexx" Link "ARexx"} for more information.


@EndNode

@Node "Cache" "EqEd.guide/Cache"
@Toc "Preference window"

Cache
=====

   The creation of the fontcaches used in @{"Output" Link "Output"} are done here.  This
is useful, if you want to make a cache for IFF output,  use a different
resolution or different fonts.

   First make sure you have have setup the paths in @{"Fonts" Link "Fonts"} correctly and
then enter the wanted resolution and font size. If you have XPK
installed you can select to pack the fontcache and thus save a lot of
diskspace. Now enter what you want to call the fontcache and finally
press "Save fontcache". This will take a long time, depending on whether
you have a coprocessor or not. On a 68000 it might take up to half an
hour!


@EndNode

@Node "Keys" "EqEd.guide/Keys"
@Next "Menus"
@Prev "Preference window"
@Toc "Main"

Keys
====

   The keyboard is the fastest way to enter something and it therefore
gives access to everything except a few of the menus. The input
available can be divided into several groups:

   Ordinary letters, numbers and such: These are entered using the usual
keyboard keys. Remember that greek letters can be assigned to the
keyboard using the @{"Set Key" Link "Set Key"} menu.

   Movement: This is done using the four arrowkeys. For faster movement
use them while pressing the Ctrl or Alt-key.

   Editing: Backspace and Del work as they always does.

   Tabulator key: This is for entering @{"Multiple columns" Link "Multiple columns"} expressions.

   Return key: This is for entering @{"Multiple lines" Link "Multiple lines"} expressions.

   Symbols and functions: These are normally selected with the mouse,
but shortcut keys can be made with @{"Set Key" Link "Set Key"}.

   Menus: Most menus has keyboard shortcuts. They are in the standard
form: Right-Amiga + key. An exception is the ARexx scripts, which can be
accessed through F1-F5, see @{"Script names" Link "Script names"}.

   Help: Pressing Helpkey will bring up this document and find the
appropriate section containing information on the gadget or menu the
cursor is placed over.


@EndNode

@Node "Multiple columns" "EqEd.guide/Multiple columns"
@Next "Multiple lines"
@Toc "Keys"

Multiple columns
================

   When using several lines in an expression, see @{"Multiple lines" Link "Multiple lines"}, it is
often necessary to align parts of lines under each other, for instance
having several lines with a "=" in the middle. It is also possible to
make very simple tables - see @{"Tables" Link "Tables"}.

   Tabs are used in the same ways as in modern wordprocessors. You setup
tabstops and how to align the tabs in the @{"Horizontal ruler" Link "Horizontal ruler"}, and then
add the different columns by pressing the tab key. If no tabstop has
been setup, it will simply add half an inch.  Note that when inside a
matrix tabstops are setup from the beginning of the matrix.


@EndNode

@Node "Multiple lines" "EqEd.guide/Multiple lines"
@Next "About"
@Prev "Multiple columns"
@Toc "Keys"

Multiple lines
==============

   Some expressions is too large for a single line, or one might want
to make some manipulations of the expression and then you need the
multiline function.  Simply press the Return key and the current line
is split into two at the position of the cursor. Joining the lines
again is done with Backspace or Del. You have to be on the outmost
level of line or the Return key will just work as the arrow down key -
this means you can't split a line in the middle of a fraction for
instance.

   When you are in a matrix, you will instead add extra lines to the
matrix - this is the only way to add lines to matrices.


@EndNode

@Node "Menus" "EqEd.guide/Menus"
@Next "Tables"
@Prev "Keys"
@Toc "Main"

Menus
=====

   EqEd has the following menus:

   Project:       Edit:    Modes:      Prefs:              ARexx

@{"About" Link "About"}        @{"Mark" Link "Mark"}        @{"Roman" Link "Roman"}     @{"Set Prefs" Link "Set Prefs"}      @{"Execute Script" Link "Execute Script"}

@{"New" Link "New"}          @{"Cut" Link "Cut"}         @{"Greek" Link "Greek"}     @{"Set Key" Link "Set Key"}        @{"Script names" Link "Script names"}

@{"Open" Link "Open"}         @{"Copy" Link "Copy"}        @{"Extra" Link "Extra"}     @{"Output Format" Link "Output Format"}    ...

@{"Insert Ascii" Link "Insert Ascii"} @{"Paste" Link "Paste"}       @{"Mathmode" Link "Mathmode"}  @{"Show symbolbar" Link "Show symbolbar"}   ...

@{"Save" Link "Save"}         @{"Select all" Link "Select all"}  @{"Textmode" Link "Textmode"}  @{"Show left ruler" Link "Show left ruler"}  ...

@{"Save As" Link "Save As"}      @{"Enter ASCII" Link "Enter ASCII"} @{"Boldmode" Link "Boldmode"}  @{"Show top ruler" Link "Show top ruler"}   ...

@{"Save To Clip" Link "Save To Clip"} @{"Copy Ruler" Link "Copy Ruler"}  @{"Line Size" Link "Line Size"} @{"Symbol Windows" Link "Symbol Windows"}

@{"Quit" Link "Quit"}         @{"Paste Ruler" Link "Paste Ruler"}             @{"Save prefs" Link "Save prefs"}

              @{"Clear Ruler" Link "Clear Ruler"}

              @{"Edit Tabs" Link "Edit Tabs"}


@EndNode

@Node "About" "EqEd.guide/About"
@Next "New"
@Prev "Multiple lines"
@Toc "Menus"

About
=====

   Tells who made the program - see also @{"The Author" Link "The Author"}.


@EndNode

@Node "New" "EqEd.guide/New"
@Next "Open"
@Prev "About"
@Toc "Menus"

New
===

   Erases the current expression after you confirm it.


@EndNode

@Node "Open" "EqEd.guide/Open"
@Next "Insert Ascii"
@Prev "New"
@Toc "Menus"

Open
====

   Opens a requester, so you can select an saved expression to be
loaded. It can load expression saved with @{"Embedded" Link "Embedded"} on except LaTeX, but
that is being worked on.


@EndNode

@Node "Insert Ascii" "EqEd.guide/Insert Ascii"
@Next "Save"
@Prev "Open"
@Toc "Menus"

Insert Ascii
============

   Inserts an ASCII file at the cursor position - most useful when
making tables. Note that real tabs (ASCII 9) are used for making tabs!


@EndNode

@Node "Save" "EqEd.guide/Save"
@Next "Save As"
@Prev "Insert Ascii"
@Toc "Menus"

Save
====

   The current expression is saved to disk in the format selected in
@{"Output Format" Link "Output Format"}.  If no name is given to the expression, a requester will
be opened.

   If you mark an area with the mouse or the @{"Mark" Link "Mark"} menu, and select save,
it will ask if it should save the marked area or the whole area.


@EndNode

@Node "Save As" "EqEd.guide/Save As"
@Next "Save To Clip"
@Prev "Save"
@Toc "Menus"

Save As
=======

   This works as @{"Save" Link "Save"} except it always pops up a requester.


@EndNode

@Node "Save To Clip" "EqEd.guide/Save To Clip"
@Next "Quit"
@Prev "Save As"
@Toc "Menus"

Save To Clip
============

   Instead of saving the expression on disk, it is possible to save in
clipboard unit 0, for direct insertion in a wordprocessor. This is not
possible when output is either @{"PostScript" Link "PostScript"} or @{"Native" Link "Native"}, but then it isn't
very useful to save those to the clipboard.


@EndNode

@Node "Quit" "EqEd.guide/Quit"
@Next "Mark"
@Prev "Save To Clip"
@Toc "Menus"

Quit
====

   Should be obvious.


@EndNode

@Node "Mark" "EqEd.guide/Mark"
@Next "Cut"
@Prev "Quit"
@Toc "Menus"

Mark
====

   This is an alternative way of marking a block - see @{"Editing Area" Link "Editing Area"} for
the other way. Place the cursor at one end of the part you want to mark,
select Mark and move to the end. When the block is selected, you can
@{"Cut" Link "Cut"}, @{"Copy" Link "Copy"} or change @{"Mode" Link "Mode"}. Selecting Mark again or entering text while
marking will abort the marking, and in the latter case delete the
marked. You can also save the marked see @{"Save" Link "Save"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Cut" "EqEd.guide/Cut"
@Next "Copy"
@Prev "Mark"
@Toc "Menus"

Cut
===

   This one removes an marked block of the expression for later
insertion at another point. Insertion is done using @{"Paste" Link "Paste"}. Note that it
does not use the usual clipboarddevice as the expression isn't stored
in a standard format!


@EndNode

@Node "Copy" "EqEd.guide/Copy"
@Next "Paste"
@Prev "Cut"
@Toc "Menus"

Copy
====

   Works as @{"Cut" Link "Cut"} except it doesn't remove anything, it just stores a copy
for later insertion.


@EndNode

@Node "Paste" "EqEd.guide/Paste"
@Next "Select all"
@Prev "Copy"
@Toc "Menus"

Paste
=====

   This inserts an expression previously copied or cut using @{"Copy" Link "Copy"} or
@{"Cut" Link "Cut"}.  This is nice when having to use the same subexpression several
times!


@EndNode

@Node "Select all" "EqEd.guide/Select all"
@Next "Enter ASCII"
@Prev "Paste"
@Toc "Menus"

Select all
==========

   For marking the whole document easily.


@EndNode

@Node "Enter ASCII" "EqEd.guide/Enter ASCII"
@Next "Copy Ruler"
@Prev "Select all"
@Toc "Menus"

Enter ASCII
===========

   This allows you to enter characters by their ASCII value.


@EndNode

@Node "Copy Ruler" "EqEd.guide/Copy Ruler"
@Next "Paste Ruler"
@Prev "Enter ASCII"
@Toc "Menus"

Copy Ruler
==========

   This copies the current tabsetting to an internal buffer for later
insertion with @{"Paste Ruler" Link "Paste Ruler"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Paste Ruler" "EqEd.guide/Paste Ruler"
@Next "Clear Ruler"
@Prev "Copy Ruler"
@Toc "Menus"

Paste Ruler
===========

   Sets the current tabsettings - as displayed in the @{"Horizontal ruler" Link "Horizontal ruler"} -
to what was stored with @{"Copy Ruler" Link "Copy Ruler"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Clear Ruler" "EqEd.guide/Clear Ruler"
@Next "Edit Tabs"
@Prev "Paste Ruler"
@Toc "Menus"

Clear Ruler
===========

   Clears the tabsettings for the current line. Note that this doesn't
necesarily mean that there won't be any tabstops - it will use the same
tabstops as the previous line.


@EndNode

@Node "Edit Tabs" "EqEd.guide/Edit Tabs"
@Next "Roman"
@Prev "Clear Ruler"
@Toc "Menus"

Edit Tabs
=========

   This opens a window, where you can edit the tabstops with great
accuracy.  Useful when making tables. Note that you can also load and
save the tabstop setting, but I doubt that is to much use.


@EndNode

@Node "Roman" "EqEd.guide/Roman"
@Next "Greek"
@Prev "Edit Tabs"
@Toc "Menus"

Roman
=====

   Another way to change @{"Font" Link "Font"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Greek" "EqEd.guide/Greek"
@Next "Extra"
@Prev "Roman"
@Toc "Menus"

Greek
=====

   Another way to change @{"Font" Link "Font"}


@EndNode

@Node "Extra" "EqEd.guide/Extra"
@Next "Mathmode"
@Prev "Greek"
@Toc "Menus"

Extra
=====

   Another way to change @{"Font" Link "Font"}


@EndNode

@Node "Mathmode" "EqEd.guide/Mathmode"
@Next "Textmode"
@Prev "Extra"
@Toc "Menus"

Mathmode
========

   Another way to change @{"Mode" Link "Mode"}


@EndNode

@Node "Textmode" "EqEd.guide/Textmode"
@Next "Boldmode"
@Prev "Mathmode"
@Toc "Menus"

Textmode
========

   Another way to change @{"Mode" Link "Mode"}


@EndNode

@Node "Boldmode" "EqEd.guide/Boldmode"
@Next "Line Size"
@Prev "Textmode"
@Toc "Menus"

Boldmode
========

   Another way to change @{"Mode" Link "Mode"}


@EndNode

@Node "Line Size" "EqEd.guide/Line Size"
@Next "Set Prefs"
@Prev "Boldmode"
@Toc "Menus"

Line Size
=========

   When entering an expressions the font gets smaller and smaller the
deeper the expression is nested in fractions, root... This might not
always look quite good, and the four submenus allows to override the
default choice of font size. Selecting one of the font sizes will
change the current part of expression and any level under it
accordingly. Try it and you will understand immediately.


@EndNode

@Node "Set Prefs" "EqEd.guide/Set Prefs"
@Next "Set Key"
@Prev "Line Size"
@Toc "Menus"

Set Prefs
=========

   Opens the @{"Preference window" Link "Preference window"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Set Key" "EqEd.guide/Set Key"
@Next "Output Format"
@Prev "Set Prefs"
@Toc "Menus"

Set Key
=======

   Using the toolbars can be bothersome when having to enter the same
symbol or function several times, so it is possible to make your own
shortcut keys. Start by selecting the Set Key menu. Now the title of
the window changes to "Press key to set". Hold down the shifts, alts
and so on that you want to have and press the key you want to program.
Note that right shift is different from left shift! Again the title
changes to "Choose symbol for key".  Now either choose a function, a
symbol or press a letter. Title will change back to default. If you
selected a symbol or function pressing the shortcut key will enter that
symbol or function at the cursor. If you selected a letter, the letter
will be entered, but in the @{"Font" Link "Font"} and @{"Mode" Link "Mode"} which was active when the
shortcut key was entered!

   Example:

   You want to enter an expression with lots of phi's, so you want to
place that on right alt-f. Start by changing to greek font.  Select
@{"Set Key" Link "Set Key"}. Hold right alt down and press f. Press f to get the phi
programmed. Now every time you need a phi just press alt-f.

   The shortcut keys are saved using @{"Save prefs" Link "Save prefs"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Output Format" "EqEd.guide/Output Format"
@Prev "Set Key"
@Toc "Menus"

Output Format
=============

   EqEd can save in five different formats and if you selected @{"Embedded" Link "Embedded"}
it can read the output again, except for @{"LaTeX" Link "LaTeX"}.

   These are submenus, which select the type of output:

@{"Embedded" Link "Embedded"}

@{"IFF" Link "IFF"}

@{"Native" Link "Native"}

@{"LaTeX" Link "LaTeX"}

@{"PostScript" Link "PostScript"}

@{"PostScript+Preview" Link "PostScript+Preview"}


@EndNode

@Node "Embedded" "EqEd.guide/Embedded"
@Next "IFF"
@Toc "Output Format"

Embedded
========

   With the Embedded menu you select whether EqEd shall include its own
format in the output files or not. If it is selected all generated
output can be read again. Currently LaTeX ignores this menu.


@EndNode

@Node "IFF" "EqEd.guide/IFF"
@Next "Native"
@Prev "Embedded"
@Toc "Output Format"

IFF
===

   The expression is saved as a black and white bitplane for inclusion
in all wordprocessors.


@EndNode

@Node "Native" "EqEd.guide/Native"
@Next "LaTeX"
@Prev "IFF"
@Toc "Output Format"

Native
======

   Saved so that it can be read again by the program, and reedited.
This is somewhat obsolete as EqEd now can read both IFF and Postscript,
if you select the @{"Embedded" Link "Embedded"} menu.


@EndNode

@Node "LaTeX" "EqEd.guide/LaTeX"
@Next "PostScript"
@Prev "Native"
@Toc "Output Format"

LaTeX
=====

   EqEd tries to save it for inclusion in a LaTeX document so that it
will look like the display.


@EndNode

@Node "PostScript" "EqEd.guide/PostScript"
@Next "PostScript+Preview"
@Prev "LaTeX"
@Toc "Output Format"

PostScript
==========

   Save as an encapsulated postscript file (EPS) for inclusion in
modern wordprocessors. Suggested save method for highquality output.

   Also see @{"PostScript+Preview" Link "PostScript+Preview"}.


@EndNode

@Node "PostScript+Preview" "EqEd.guide/PostScript+Preview"
@Prev "PostScript"
@Toc "Output Format"

Postscript with preview picture
===============================

   Save as an encapsulated postscript file (EPS) for inclusion in
modern wordprocessors. Suggested save method for highquality output.
The difference from @{"PostScript" Link "PostScript"} is that a preview image generated and
included in the file. This is supported by Finalwriter and perhaps also
other programs.


@EndNode

@Node "Show symbolbar" "EqEd.guide/Show symbolbar"
@Next "Show left ruler"
@Toc "Menus"

Show symbolbar
==============

   Toggles the @{"User buttons" Link "User buttons"} on and off.


@EndNode

@Node "Show left ruler" "EqEd.guide/Show left ruler"
@Next "Show top ruler"
@Prev "Show symbolbar"
@Toc "Menus"

Show left ruler
===============

   Toggles the @{"Vertical ruler" Link "Vertical ruler"} on and off.


@EndNode

@Node "Show top ruler" "EqEd.guide/Show top ruler"
@Prev "Show left ruler"
@Toc "Menus"

Show top ruler
==============

   Toggles the @{"Horizontal ruler" Link "Horizontal ruler"} on and off.


@EndNode

@Node "Symbol Windows" "EqEd.guide/Symbol Windows"
@Toc "Menus"

Symbol Windows
==============

   This contains four submenus, which allows setting the Fast close
option for all of the symbol windows at a time and likewise to change
their orientation. See @{"Symbols" Link "Symbols"} for an explaination of these options


@EndNode

@Node "Save prefs" "EqEd.guide/Save prefs"
@Next "Execute Script"
@Toc "Menus"

Save prefs
==========

   This saves you shortcut keys made with @{"Set Key" Link "Set Key"} and resolution set by
@{"Set Prefs" Link "Set Prefs"} into a file called EqEd.config in EnvArc:.  It also keeps
track of the open windows, their position and so on.  Finally it also
saves the contents of the @{"User buttons" Link "User buttons"}.

   The "Save" button in the @{"Preference window" Link "Preference window"} does the same.


@EndNode

@Node "Execute Script" "EqEd.guide/Execute Script"
@Prev "Save prefs"
@Toc "Menus"

Execute Script
==============

   This will popup a filerequester where you can select a ARexx script
to start. See @{"ARexx" Link "ARexx"} for more information


@EndNode

@Node "Script names" "EqEd.guide/Script names"
@Toc "Menus"

Script names
============

   These five menus provides access to scripts installed in the
@{"Preference window" Link "Preference window"}. They are also available by pressing F1-F5.


@EndNode

@Node "Tables" "EqEd.guide/Tables"
@Next "ARexx"
@Prev "Menus"
@Toc "Main"

Tables
======

   EqEd v0.96 can create tables, but it is still very primitive and can
be improved in many ways. First of all you should know what you want
your table to look like from the beginning otherwise you risk having to
change the look of every cell individually afterwards! Unless you have
your data in a ASCII file, you want to include, you should setup the
table with lines and such before you enter your data.

   You can either use the whole "equation" or a matrix as a table.
First you setup the vertical coloumns, where you want vertical lines.
This is done by placing the tabstop that is just a vertical line in the
@{"Horizontal ruler" Link "Horizontal ruler"}. This works as a left-aligned tabstop, except it also
marks the end of a cell. Now you can place your first @{"Lines" Link "Lines"} around the
first cell, and then move on to the next cell by pressing the TAB-key.
Note that next cell will have the same bottom, top and right line as
the first cell, so that most at the time you don't need to set the
lines for the new cell. Continue to make cells on the first line, until
you have enough cells, and then press RETURN. When you press TAB, you
will see that it uses the same line thickness as in the first line,
again to save you work. If you think the cells are not high enough, you
can as always add extra linespace by dragging in the lines in the
@{"Vertical ruler" Link "Vertical ruler"}

   When the table is finished you can start entering the data. Often you
will discover that a cell is too small or you have forgotten a cell.
You can make cell wider by moving the tabstop - hold down SHIFT while
you do it and the the rest keeps their distance! A new cell is added by
adding a tabstop, and fixing the lines. You can use @{"Edit Tabs" Link "Edit Tabs"} if you
want your cells to have the same width.

   As said before the table handling is very primitive, and the worst
is probably that you cannot mark cells and then change all their lines
at a time. Also the lines aren't bound to the tabstops so if you remove
a tabstop or writes more than there can be in a cell it will probably
look strange. I am very open to suggestion on how to improve this.  I
could also imagine making a kind of list of standard tables, which sets
everything immediately - I have seen this in MS-Word.

   When working with tables and matrices it is very important you use
the same font on screen as in postscript and IFF output, because
otherwise some of the text might not fit into a cell and this produce
strange looking output! There also seems to be a little difference in
postscript output and the screen, so a good rule is leave a little
space free to the left of each tabstop.


@EndNode

@Node "ARexx" "EqEd.guide/ARexx"
@Next "Hints"
@Prev "Tables"
@Toc "Main"

ARexx
=====

   EqEd now supports a few ARexx commands and can also launch ARexx
scripts with the @{"Execute Script" Link "Execute Script"} menu. The purpose of the commands
currently implemented is to allow easy insertion of equations into
wordprocessors, which has ARexx capabilities. For easy access to the
scripts you can also install the scripts on function keys - see @{"Rexx" Link "Rexx"}.

   C. David Shaffer has made some ARexx scripts, which integrates EqEd
into FinalWriter. Unfortunately FinalWriter's screen isn't public, so
you have to run EqEd on a separate screen, but someone is working on a
hack to circumvent this.

   The scripts are placed in the Rexx drawer, and do the following:

   * "EqEdFront.rexx" starts EqEd if it isn't running and de-iconifies
     it, if it is iconified. For the best result set the public screen
     for EqEd to "FrontMost" in MUI-Prefs. It is supposed to be
     executed from FinalWriter.  If you have selected an old equation
     as the current object, when you call the script, it will
     automaticly be loaded into EqEd, so you can edit old equations
     easily! This only works if it was saved with the "InsertFW.eqed"
     script though.   Install this script in the user menu in
     FinalWriter, so you have easy access.

   * "InsertFW.rexx" is to be run from EqEd and will insert the current
     equation into FinalWriter in @{"PostScript+Preview" Link "PostScript+Preview"} format with
     @{"Embedded" Link "Embedded"} version of the equation. If no name is given it will ask
     via RexxReqTools, so that is needed. If you are editing an old
     equation, which was loaded with "EqEdFront.rexx" it will be
     replaced in FW with the new one!  This script also circumvents
     FW's bug in the INSERTIMAGE command.

   * "FwToFront.eqed" will simply put FW to the front.

   I'm very interested in scripts for other wordprocessors or improved
ones for FinalWriter. If you are missing some ARexx commands in EqEd
please let me know.

   EqEd's ARexx port is called EQED.1 and besides the standard command
it supports:

@{"GetOutput" Link "GetOutput"}

@{"SetOutput" Link "SetOutput"}

@{"GetName" Link "GetName"}

@{"SetName" Link "SetName"}

@{"Save " Link "Save "}

@{"Load" Link "Load"}

@{"New " Link "New "}

@{"EqEdToFront" Link "EqEdToFront"}

@{"Prefs" Link "Prefs"}

@{"SetFontSize" Link "SetFontSize"}

   NOTE: MUI seems to like the ARexx commands to be placed inside " -
this is definately needed when using @{"Prefs" Link "Prefs"}.


@EndNode

@Node "GetOutput" "EqEd.guide/GetOutput"
@Next "SetOutput"
@Toc "ARexx"

GetOutput
=========

   Takes no arguments, but as an result it returns the current type of
@{"Output Format" Link "Output Format"}.  This is one of the following five
"IFF","NATIVE","LaTeX","EPS","PREVIEWPS".  It is followed by either
"EMBEDDED" or "NOEMBED" to reflect on the status of the @{"Embedded" Link "Embedded"} menu.


@EndNode

@Node "SetOutput" "EqEd.guide/SetOutput"
@Next "GetName"
@Prev "GetOutput"
@Toc "ARexx"

SetOutput
=========

   Takes as parameter one of the five strings returned by @{"GetOutput" Link "GetOutput"} and
sets @{"Output Format" Link "Output Format"} accordingly. As a optional argument you can add
"EMBEDDED" or "NOEMBED" to change the @{"Embedded" Link "Embedded"} status also.


@EndNode

@Node "GetName" "EqEd.guide/GetName"
@Next "SetName"
@Prev "SetOutput"
@Toc "ARexx"

GetName
=======

   Returns the current filename with complete path.


@EndNode

@Node "SetName" "EqEd.guide/SetName"
@Next "Save "
@Prev "GetName"
@Toc "ARexx"

SetName
=======

   If an parameter is supplied it sets this as the current filename.
Otherwise it sets it to "Untitled".


@EndNode

@Node "Save " "EqEd.guide/Save "
@Next "Load"
@Prev "SetName"
@Toc "ARexx"

Save
====

   Saves the current equation under the current name or a supplied name.

   If the equation is saved in postscript format, it will return the
boundingbox and the offset from the top of the equation to the baseline
of the topmost line. The boundingbox information is provided to
circumvent the INSERTIMAGE bug in FinalWriter, while baseline
information, is to make inline equation possible.


@EndNode

@Node "Load" "EqEd.guide/Load"
@Next "New "
@Prev "Save "
@Toc "ARexx"

Load
====

   Loads the equation file, which name is supplied or it uses the
current name.


@EndNode

@Node "New " "EqEd.guide/New "
@Next "EqEdToFront"
@Prev "Load"
@Toc "ARexx"

New
===

   Delete the current equation from the window.


@EndNode

@Node "EqEdToFront" "EqEd.guide/EqEdToFront"
@Next "Prefs"
@Prev "New "
@Toc "ARexx"

EqEdToFront
===========

   Moves the EqEd screen to the front.


@EndNode

@Node "Prefs" "EqEd.guide/Prefs"
@Prev "EqEdToFront"
@Toc "ARexx"

Prefs
=====

   The Prefs command allows you to change the resolution and cachefiles
from ARexx.  The first argument decides what you kind of font you are
changing. The possibilities are SCREEN,IFF,PREVIEW - the same as in the
Preference window. After that you can supply up to three arguments, but
they are all optional:

   Cache=filename: Sets the cachename. If the cache exists the
resolution is read from the cachefile, and the rest of the arguments are
ignored.

   XDPI=number: Sets the horizontal resolution.

   YDPI=number: Sets the vertical resolution.

   In AmigaDos notation these arguments can in short be described as:
"Type/A,Cache,XDPI/N,YDPI/N"

   A simple example which sets the IFF data:

   'Prefs IFF XDPI=360 YDPI=360'


@EndNode

@Node "SetFontSize" "EqEd.guide/SetFontSize"
@Toc "ARexx"

SetFontSize
===========

   This sets the fontsize, which will be used for everything except
where fontcaches are used. This mainly means Postscript output.  Note
that there will probably be problems, if a table or matrix is saved in
another fontsize than the one used on screen!


@EndNode

@Node "Hints" "EqEd.guide/Hints"
@Next "Future"
@Prev "ARexx"
@Toc "Main"

Hints
=====

   There isn't much here right now, but if you have any suggestions
please send them to me.

@{"Speed" Link "Speed"}        - How to make it react faster

@{"FinalWriter" Link "FinalWriter"}  - How to get FinalWriter to show the equation

@{"Indiices" Link "Indiices"}


@EndNode

@Node "Speed" "EqEd.guide/Speed"
@Next "FinalWriter"
@Toc "Hints"

Speed
=====

   The main trick is to keep the window as small as possible, because
this keeps the area needed to be update to a minimum. Also running it
on its own screen with only two bitplanes will make the update a bit
faster.

   I hope to get it to be faster in the future.


@EndNode

@Node "FinalWriter" "EqEd.guide/FinalWriter"
@Next "Indiices"
@Prev "Speed"
@Toc "Hints"

FinalWriter
===========

   Manuel Lemos has released a file called "FWEPSPatches.lha" to aminet,
which should fix most problems with FinalWriter, but if that doesn't
work, maybe some of the following will.

   I have had reports of problems from people who couldn't get
FinalWriter to display the equations, it just displayed a blank box.
Now that the @{"PostScript+Preview" Link "PostScript+Preview"} is working correctly, this problem will
probably first be apparent when trying to print to a non-postscript
printer. Try to set a equation to FULL picture and see if it gets
rendered correctly.

   If there is problem, it is probably because FinalWriter cannot find
the fonts. You will need to edit the file "init.ps" in the FinalWriter
directory called "fwfiles". You need to find the lines containing:

   dup FontDirectory exch known not         % Not in FontDirectory?

   { dup (PSFonts:) () loadfont            % Try to load from PSFonts:

   } if

   Make sure there isn't any leading % characters.

   If you have copied or moved the fonts to somewhere you have assign'ed
"PSFonts:", everything should be OK, otherwise change the "PSFonts:" to
the path of the fonts!

   Finally you can run a program like SnoopDos or DosTrace, to see if
there is some file it cannot find!


@EndNode

@Node "Indiices" "EqEd.guide/Indiices"
@Prev "FinalWriter"
@Toc "Hints"

Indiices
========

   I've gotten some letters from people, who has had some difficulties
with placing powers above indiices, e.g like this:

    2    2    2

   x  + x  + x

    1    2    3

   Sorry about the bad example, but Texinfo isn't really made for this
kind of text.

   To enter this you simply enter the 'x', select either the index
symbol or the power symbol and enter '1' or '2'. Now press the right
arrowkey.  This will place the cursor after the symbol. If you now
select the index symbol or the power symbol, it will be place
above/under the previous number and you get what you want. The
important thing is that the cursor is placed to the immediate right of
the index/power, otherwise EqEd will generate a new symbol instead of
making an extra line in the old one.


@EndNode

@Node "Future" "EqEd.guide/Future"
@Next "Register"
@Prev "Hints"
@Toc "Main"

Future
======

   EqEd is by no means finished. I have a lot of things I want to put
in it before reaching the version 1.00, which won't be a betarelease.
I'm releasing this as a public betaversion, because I want to get some
feedback from people who would actually need to include expressions in
the documents.

   As I will be spending most of my summer at CERN, I won't be able to
work on EqEd until September.

   Here is a list of some the things that I have on my to do list and
might be included in the next version (v0.98):

   * More AREXX commands, most notably it should support commands for
     entering equations.

   * Reading LaTex output.

   * The @{"Tables" Link "Tables"} part might be removed again since Final Writer 5 is
     supposed to feature these.

   * Localize all texts and perhaps manuals.

   * Clip with often used subexpression or just a simple macrofunction.

   * A function to list userdefined keys.

   * Undo function. Might just be simple undo or it might remember
     whole sequences

   * Improve the overall speed.

   * Improve manual.

   Please mail me any suggestion I can add to the list, and even if it
is on the list it might be a good idea to send me some mail, so I know
what to concentrate on.


@EndNode

@Node "Register" "EqEd.guide/Register"
@Next "The Author"
@Prev "Future"
@Toc "Main"

Register
========

   As this is a betarelease there is no shareware fee, and currently I
have no intention of putting one on the final version. I do, however,
ask you to register by sending me (see @{"The Author" Link "The Author"}) your name, address,
type of machine and most importantly your opinions, suggestions and
bugreports.  This allows me to see if anybody at all is interested and
gives me maximum amount of feedback. Please write as much as you can,
ranging from hating MUI, wanting exponents a pixel higher to new output
formats and AREXX-commands.


@EndNode

@Node "The Author" "EqEd.guide/The Author"
@Next "WWW-Page"
